@chapter Installation
@cindex installation

The source code of the package is available at

@center @code{http://www.nersc.gov/~kewu/trlan.tar.gz}.

@noindent This document is distributed with the package and is
also separately available at

@center @code{http://www.nersc.gov/~kewu/ps/trlan-ug.ps}.  

@noindent The package may be unpacked by
@smallexample
tar -xzf trlan.tar.gz
@end smallexample
@noindent If you @code{tar} program does not recognize flag @code{z},
you can unpack it in two steps
@smallexample
gunzip trlan.tar.gz
tar -xf trlan.tar
@end smallexample
@noindent After this, the files in the package will be unpacked into a
directory called @file{TRLan}.

To install the package, you will need a @code{Fortran 90} compiler, the
@code{BLAS} and @code{LAPACK} libraries.  On parallel machines, MPI is
also needed.  The compiler name and the options used are specified in
the file called @file{Make.inc}.  A number of examples are provided in
the file for different machines.  If your compiler name and library
locations are same as one of the examples, you can uncomment the
section, comment out the default values, and use the settings.  If your
compiler has a different name or the libraries are located at a
different place, you will need to modify the file to refer to their
correct values.  The package may be compiled into one of the two library
files @code{libtrlan.a} and @code{libtrlan_mpi.a} where the former is
the sequential version of the package and the latter is the parallel
version.  To generate them go to @file{TRLan} and type
@smallexample
make libtrlan.a
@exdent or
make libtrlan_mpi.a
@end smallexample

To compile the examples, go to the appropriate subdirectory in
@file{examples}.  If you are on a sequential or a shared memory computer
and there is no subdirectory that matches your computer, the source code
in the @code{SUN} directory can be used.  The examples in @file{T3E} and
@file{psp} can be run on parallel machines that support MPI.
@file{Makefile} in the @file{T3E} and @file{psp} directories are only
tested on a Cray T3E.  They will need modification in order to be used
elsewhere.  The examples in directory @file{psp} also need a special
supporting library called P_SPARSLIB, read the file @file{README} before
try to use it.

There are three examples in most example directories (except
@file{psp}), @code{simple}, @code{simple77} and @code{simplec}.  These
are three programs should be doing the same thing using three different
languages.  The executables can be generated by @code{make}
@smallexample
make simple simplec simple77
@end smallexample
They should output the same eigenvalues, however the actual printout may
differ slightly due floating-point round-off errors.

For further questions, consult the @file{README} files in the
directories.  To report errors in the installation procedure or suggest
improvements, the authors can be reached at @code{kwu@@lbl.gov} (Kesheng
Wu) and @code{hdsimon@@lbl.gov} (Horst Simon).


@node    Example, TRL_INFO module,  Installation,      Top
@chapter A small example

This is a simple example in @code{Fortran 90}.  It is short because we
have used a very simple matrix and used default parameters wherever
possible.  It uses MPI to handle data communication required by TRLAN.
This example comes with the distribution of the source code in directory
@file{examples/T3E}.  The name of the file is @file{s1.f90} and on T3E
is can be compiled by @code{make s1} which generates the executable
@code{s1}.

@cindex small example
@cindex example
@smallexample
!!! a really simple example of how to use TRLAN
Program simple
  Use trl_info
  Use trl_interface
  Implicit None
  Include 'mpif.h'
  ! local variable declaration
  Integer, Parameter :: nrow=100, lohi=-1, ned=5, maxlan=40, mev=10
  Double Precision :: eval(mev), evec(nrow, mev)
  Type(trl_info_t) :: info
  Integer :: i
  External diag_op  ! name of the matrix-vector multiplication routine
  Call MPI_INIT(i)  ! initialize MPI
  ! initialize info -- tell TRLAN to compute NED smallest eigenvalues
  Call trl_init_info(info, nrow, maxlan, lohi, ned)
  ! call TRLAN to compute the eigenvalues
  Call trlan(diag_op, info, nrow, mev, eval, evec, nrow)
  Call trl_print_info(info, nrow+nrow)
  If (info%my_pe .Eq. 0) Then
     write (6, FMT=100) (i, eval(i), i=1,info%nec)
  End If
100 Format('E(', I1, ') = ', 1PG25.17)
  Call MPI_finalize(i)
End Program simple
!!!
! a simple matrix-vector multiplications routine
! defines a diagonal matrix with value (1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, ...)
!!!
Subroutine diag_op(nrow, ncol, xin, ldx, yout, ldy)
  Implicit None
  Integer, Intent(in) :: nrow, ncol, ldx, ldy
  Double Precision, Dimension(ldx*ncol), Intent(in) :: xin
  Double Precision, Dimension(ldy*ncol), Intent(out) :: yout
  Include 'mpif.h'
  ! local variables
  Integer :: i, j, ioff, joff, doff
  Call MPI_COMM_RANK(MPI_COMM_WORLD, i, j)
  doff = nrow*i
  Do j = 1, ncol
     ioff = (j-1)*ldx
     joff = (j-1)*ldy
     Do i = 1, nrow
        yout(joff+i) = (doff+i)*(doff+i)*xin(ioff+i)
     End Do
  End Do
End Subroutine diag_op
@end smallexample

There are two parts in this example, the main program and the
matrix-vector multiplication subroutine.  The main program sets up the
@code{info} variable to carry information to and from TRLAN, calls
TRLAN, and prints the information carried out in @code{info} and the
eigenvalues computed.  Here is a short explanation of the arguments to
@code{trl_init_info}.

@smallexample
  call trl_init_info(info,      ! the variable to be set
                     nrow=100,  ! there are 100 rows on each processor
                     maxlan=40, ! maximum Lanczos basis size is 40
                     lohi=-1,   ! compute the smallest eigenvalues
                     ned=5)     ! compute 5 eigenvalues
@end smallexample

@noindent  The calling sequence of TRLAN is fairly simple because all
the gory details are hidden inside @code{info}.  The following listing
describes the information required by TRLAN to solve an eigenvalue
problem.

@smallexample
  call trlan(diag_op,           ! matrix-vector multiplication routine
             info,              ! what eigenvalues to compute, etc.
             nrow,              ! 100 rows on this processor
             mev,               ! number of eigenpairs can be stored in
                                ! eval and evec
             eval,              ! real(8) :: eval(mev)
                                ! array to store eigenvalue
             evec,              ! real(8) :: evec(lde,mev)
                                ! array to store the eigenvectors
             lde)               ! the leading dimension of evec
@end smallexample

@noindent The content of @code{info} and the eigenvalues are printed
separately.  The content of @code{info} is printed by calling
@code{trl_print_info} which accepts two arguments, @code{info} to be
printed and the number of floating-point operations used for one
matrix-vector multiplication on this processor.  The second parameter is
needed because the matrix-vector multiplication is user-supplied.  The
information is used to compute the speed of the matrix-vector
multiplication and the speed of the whole program.  It can be ignored,
in which case @code{trl_print_info} will leave the related fields blank.

The short matrix-vector multiplication routine, @code{diag_op}, performs
multiplication with a very simple matrix, @code{diag(1, 4, 9, ...)}.
The example tries to find 5 smallest eigenvalues of this matrix, 1, 4,
9, 16, 25.  The following is the output from a run on a T3E/900 located
at the National Energy Research Supercomputing Center@footnote{Information
about the National Energy Research Supercomputing Center can be found on
the web at @code{http://www.nersc.gov/}.}.

